Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Umar Abubakar¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset which includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 trips taken during the month of February 2019 in the dataset with 16 features (duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip). The features consists of different types (ints, floats, strings, datetime, and categorical variables.

integers: ['duration_sec']

floats: ['start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude']

strings: ['start_station_id', 'start_station_name', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'bike_id']

datetime: ['start_time', 'end_time']

categorical: ['user_type', 'member_gender', 'bike_share_for_all_trip']

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in finding out the features that affect ride duration and the number of trips taken per day, month, and year.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I am proceeding with the assumption that the distance between the start_station and end_station location will have strong effect on the duration of the ride. I also think that age of the members, user_type, member_gender also determines the number of rides taken.

In this section we will be:

  • gathering additional data for the remaining months of the year
  • exploring the dataset and cleaning issues found within
  • deriving additional columns that support our analysis

#function to convert columns of a dataframe to datetime object
def date_time(df, cols):
    ''' The function takes as input a dataframe and a list of columns to convert. '''
    for col in cols:
        df[col] = pd.to_datetime(df[col])

#function call to convert dataframe columns to datetime object

#list of columns to convert to category type

def to_type(df, cols, d_type='str'):
    ''' The function takes as input a dataframe, a list of columns and the keyword argument d_type which specifies the type to convert to. '''
    for col in cols:
        df[col] = df[col].astype(d_type)

#importing modules from the math package
from math import sin, cos, sqrt, atan2, radians

#function to calculate distance between two geographical locations using their latitude and longitude
def calculateDistance(row, lat1, lat2, lon1, lon2):
    lat_start = row[lat1]
    lat_end = row[lat2]
    lon_start = row[lon1]
    lon_end = row[lon2]
    R = 6373.0 # approximate radius of earth in km
    dlon = radians(lon_end - lon_start)
    dlat = radians(lat_end - lat_start)
    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat_start) * cos(lat_end) * sin(dlon / 2)**2
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))
    
    d = R * c
    return d

cols = []
ford_jan_apr['distance'] = ford_jan_apr.apply(lambda row: calculateDistance(row, 'start_station_latitude', 'end_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_longitude'), axis=1)

# function to calculate time of day
def time_day(time):
    if time.hour >= 12 and time.hour <= 16:
        return 'Afternoon'
    elif time.hour > 16 and time.hour <= 19:
        return "Evening"
    elif time.hour > 19 and time.hour <= 24:
        return "Night"
    else:
        return 'Morning'
    

# adding a new column called 'time_of_day' to the dataframe by applying the time_day() function to the 'start_time' column
ford_jan_apr['time_of_day'] = ford_jan_apr['start_time'].apply(lambda row: time_day(row))

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The analysis on the duration_sec variable showed that majority of the rides were short and under 2,000 seconds. After increasing the bins size and applying log transform on the y-axis due to the long tail of the distribution, it showed that a few rides about 100 of them have long durations with the maximum having more than 80, 000 seconds.

Initial analysis of the age variable showed a right skewed distribution with a long tail and that majority of the customers are between the ages of 20 and 60 years. After increasing the bins size and applying log transformation on the y-axis, it showed that majority of the customers are between the age of 20 and 80 years. it also showed that a few of the customers are over 100 years old. Wrong date of birth information maybe?

Analysis of the distance variable showed a right skewed distribution with a long tail and that most of the rides have short distances. Applying a log transformation on the x-axis and increasing the bins size showed that the distance of most rides is between 0.3km and 10km with the peak distance travelled for most rides at 1km.

The analysis of the user_type variable shows that most of Ford GoBike users are Subscribers, 86.7% of them while the remaining 13.3% are Customers.

The analysis of the member_gender variable show that majority of Ford GoBike users are male (74.1%) and 24.0% are female while 2.0% are other (did not specify their gender).

Of the four months of Ford GoBike systems data analysed, March recorded the highest number of rides closely followed by April and then January and February

Analysing the day of week variable showed that majority of the rides were taken during the week days while the weekends see less trips.

Analysing the time_of_day variable showed that a lot of users take rides during the Morning, followed by Evening and Afternoon. Night's has the lowest number of rides recorded.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

All the distribution of the three variable duration_sec, age, distance analyzed were highly skewed to the right so log transformation was applied to the y-axis of duration_sec and age variables and to the x-axis of the distance variable.

The month, day_of_week, and time_of_day variables are all derived variables. They were extracted from the start_time variable which is a datetime object.

The distance variable is also a derived variable. It was calculated using the start station latitude, end station latitude, start station longitude and end station longitude together with the radius of the earth in kilometres.

These derived variables were added to the dataset to aid in the analysis of Ford GoBike systems data.

Conclusions¶

Summary of findings and steps taken during data exploration.

In conclusion, By exploring the Ford GoBike System Data (January - April, 2019) we were able to discern some information:

  • There was a decline in the duration and distance of rides taken from January to February and that while duration increased from February to April, distance only increased from February to March followed by a sharp decrease between March and April.
  • there is a positive correlation between distance and duration. That is, the higher the distance the higher the duration.
  • males take the most rides at all times of day followed by females and other (unspecified gender)
  • that members between the 25 and 35 clocked the highest durations with females and customers taking rides with the longest durations at all times of day, on all days of the week and in all the months of data analysed.
  • Between Ford GoBike customers and subscribers, customers tend to take the longest rides at all times of the day, on all days of the week and also in all the months (January - February) of data analysed.
  • Between Males, Females, and Other (Unspecified gender), females take the longest rides followed by Other and Males at all times of day, on all days of the week and in all four months analysed except in January where Other (Unspecified gender) was slightly higher than females. Males have rides with the shortest durations.
  • Comparing the relationships between duration, distance and categorical variables showed a surprising result that despite the percentage of males being larger than that of females and other (unspecified gender), females and other spend more time and cover more distance during their rides than males. This makes me to suspect that males maybe taking a shorter route than females and other.

    I suspect route and not speed because the distance covered by females and other is higher than that of males. if the distance were to be the same and duration different (females and other with higher durations), then I would say that males use higher speeds during their rides.
